Week 13 – Java Applet Programs
1) Applet to display a simple message

Question: Develop an applet that displays a simple message like "Hello, Welcome to Java Applet!".

Program:

import java.applet.Applet;
import java.awt.Graphics;

public class SimpleMessageApplet extends Applet {
    public void paint(Graphics g) {
        g.drawString("Hello, Welcome to Java Applet!", 50, 50);
    }
}


Explanation:

Applet class is used to create Java applets.

paint(Graphics g) method is called automatically when the applet is run.

drawString(String str, int x, int y) displays the string on the applet at coordinates (x, y).

Output:
A window will open with the text:
"Hello, Welcome to Java Applet!" at position (50,50).

HTML file to run applet:

<html>
<body>
<applet code="SimpleMessageApplet.class" width="300" height="100"></applet>
</body>
</html>

2) Applet to add two integer numbers

Question: Develop an applet that adds two integer numbers and displays the result.

Program:

import java.applet.Applet;
import java.awt.Graphics;

public class AddTwoNumbersApplet extends Applet {
    int num1 = 10;
    int num2 = 20;
    int sum;

    public void init() {
        sum = num1 + num2; // Adding two numbers
    }

    public void paint(Graphics g) {
        g.drawString("Number 1: " + num1, 50, 50);
        g.drawString("Number 2: " + num2, 50, 70);
        g.drawString("Sum: " + sum, 50, 90);
    }
}


Explanation:

init() method initializes the variables (runs when applet starts).

paint(Graphics g) displays the numbers and their sum.

sum = num1 + num2 performs addition.

Output:
The applet will display:

Number 1: 10
Number 2: 20
Sum: 30


HTML file to run applet:

<html>
<body>
<applet code="AddTwoNumbersApplet.class" width="300" height="150"></applet>
</body>
</html>

3) Applet to draw lines, rectangle, and oval

Question: Develop an applet that draws lines, rectangles, and ovals.

Program:

import java.applet.Applet;
import java.awt.Graphics;
import java.awt.Color;

public class DrawShapesApplet extends Applet {
    public void paint(Graphics g) {
        // Draw a line from (20,20) to (200,20)
        g.drawLine(20, 20, 200, 20);

        // Draw a rectangle at (50,50) with width 150 and height 80
        g.drawRect(50, 50, 150, 80);

        // Draw an oval inside rectangle at (50,150) with width 150 and height 80
        g.drawOval(50, 150, 150, 80);

        // Optional: add some color
        g.setColor(Color.RED);
        g.drawString("Line, Rectangle and Oval", 50, 260);
    }
}


Explanation:

drawLine(x1, y1, x2, y2) draws a straight line.

drawRect(x, y, width, height) draws a rectangle.

drawOval(x, y, width, height) draws an oval that fits inside the rectangle defined by x, y, width, and height.

setColor(Color.RED) changes the color of the subsequent drawing.

Output:

A line at the top.

A rectangle below the line.

An oval below the rectangle.

Text "Line, Rectangle and Oval" in red color.

HTML file to run applet:

<html>
<body>
<applet code="DrawShapesApplet.class" width="300" height="300"></applet>
</body>
</html>


✅ All three applets are ready to run in a browser or applet viewer.
